metadata.name: When we were Kids #5
metadata.description:
When we were kids.

A work that goes back to our childhood.
When I was a kid I loved spending time with my grandmother and parents, we took a lot of walks with them, looked at different houses, spent time in nature, painted and in general were very much involved in the creative component, it was my parents and grandmother who instilled in me a love for creativity.

Probably one of the few things that have survived to these days is my childhood drawings, a little funny, sloppy, but so real and sincere.

In this work I wanted to take me back to those carefree times and remember with what eagerness and zeal I tried every day to learn something new or to go further than before.

None of this would have happened without my family, for which I am truly grateful.

10% of primary sales will be donated to Cure Parkinson's, I hope all children will have a childhood where they can spend time with their loved ones.

Be patient, some variations take a little longer to render.

Press S for Save Canvas as PNG.

By aleks.ustya, @ALEKUSTN. Made with p5js.

metadata.name: Sketches:Pairs of Tails:Majestic Creatures #29
metadata.description:
Addendum to Annuls of WorSAGE (the Worshipful Society of Adventurers and Generative Explorers) XXVII.Vol.2048

There is a significantly common phenomena in which Pairs of "Tails of Majestic Creatures" are found together. Various sketches of these "Pairs" have been collated and are available, free of charge, the collectors of the initial Tails of Majestic Creatures collection based upon a recently taken collection registry snapshot. 

These sketches are available on a one per collector basis and for a limited time only after which they will no longer be accessible.

The sketches come in 2 forms - an ink and color style, and a pencil style - for which different colored paper has been used.

The digitally minded can press s to get a 5000x3000 download of a sketch.

metadata.name: isometry II - watercolor #8
metadata.description:
This piece is a marriage of sorts. It begins with my "cityscape" interactive piece originally minted on Hic Et Nunc (here: https://teia.art/objkt/439560). This piece was used as the cover of The Tickle #30, and also received a static mint on Rarible. 

Several months later, I re-visited the land of isometrics and "fake 3D" for my "isometry" piece here on fx(hash), and which you can find here: https://www.fxhash.xyz/generative/13199

I always wanted to do a true determinative piece in the style of the original "cityscapes," and this weekend I finally sat down and "ported" it to modern fx(hash) output. Since this piece and "isometry" share a commonality, I named this piece "isometry II," and added the "watercolor" as that was the original name of the piece before I minted it on H3N. 

I hope you enjoy it!

metadata.name: Outdoor #13
metadata.description:
The moon/sun, sea, and background are created randomly by p5js, along with the infrastructure, and on top of it is an image drawn with Illustrator that incorporates angled lines.
The goal of this design is to display angular ideas placed on natural elements like the moon and sea in the simplest way possible.

metadata.name: Glass Arches #42
metadata.description:
Inspired by the art of stained glass, colored and patterned parts are arranged in a network of lead strips next to each other and act as shape-forming lines.
Their brilliant appearance is caused by the property of passing light through symmetrical pieces and asymmetric of different colors and refracting light from the center.
Made by p5.js

metadata.name: Endless #41
metadata.description:
There should be a miracle in painting.
For me, what matters most is the expression of simple and basic human feelings regarding fate, the past, the future, etc
It is my opinion that art should not reflect the feelings and statements of its creator.
As a result of my experience creating works, I have learned not to impose anything on the materials of my work, but rather to demonstrate the qualities and possibilities of them.
It doesn't take many things to see a work of art; it's attractive on its own. It is the rule of the game to repeat and expand, so the outputs in the final evaluation are conceptual.

metadata.name: glee #41
metadata.description:
At this moment, She was happy.
spins and dances and laughs.
The sky was in her hands.
Her skirt was being waved by the rainbow.
Faster and faster.
Rain carried the colors with it.
All of them were spinning, dancing, and laughing together.
The whole world seemed to be laughing at her laughter.

metadata.name: Angular View #28
metadata.description:
The angle factor plays a significant role in determining how an image feels and looks.
When viewed from one angle, elements inside the frame might appear compressed and unclear, while when viewed from another angle, they might appear clear and distinct.
Choosing the right angle can encourage and guide the audience, while choosing the wrong angle can confuse and mislead him.
Therefore, when choosing the angle, one should consider aesthetic, technical, and emotional factors to present the subject to the viewer in the best light.
Depending on the angle, space and subject of the image are transformed and they can convey various meanings, including: logical visualization of space/impossible and free visualization, exaggeration and exaggeration/simplicity, stillness/movement, insider/alienation, mysterious/reliable, and complexity.
Made by p5.js
